[30;1m231 | [0m[35m    the transformation as well as communicate between calls of `transformation` on[0m
[30;1m232 | [0m[35m    different nodes. The `depth_context` limits this communication to descendants[0m

[30;1m470 | [0m[35mtring exactly like ``s"``, but it prints that string to standard output. This is good for short mess[0m
[30;1m471 | [0m[35m- ``.`` pops an integer from the stack and prints it. If you want to peek at the top of the stack wi[0m
[30;1m472 | [0m[35m- ``.s`` prints the whole stack without modifying it. It does not print a carriage return.[0m
[30;1m473 | [0m[35m- ``cr`` prints a carriage return; it usually follows one of the above to make the output easier to [0m

[30;1m120 | [0m[35mAwkward Array broadcasting is identical to NumPy broadcasting in three respects:[0m
[30;1m121 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m122 | [0m[35m1. arrays with the same number of dimensions must match lengths (except for length 1) exactly,[0m
[30;1m123 | [0m[35m2. length-1 dimensions expand like scalars (one to many),[0m
[30;1m124 | [0m[35m3. for arrays with different numbers of dimensions, the smaller number of dimensions is expanded to [0m
[30;1m125 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m126 | [0m[35mAwkward Arrays with fixed-length dimensionsâ€”not "variable-length" or "ragged"â€”broadcast exactly like[0m

[30;1m14 | [0m[35mHow Awkward broadcasting works[0m
[30;1m15 | [0m[35m==============================[0m
[30;1m16 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m17 | [0m[35mFunctions that accept more than one array argument need to combine the elements of their array eleme[0m
[30;1m18 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m19 | [0m[35m```{code-cell} ipython3[0m

[30;1m206 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m14 | [0m[35mHow to create arrays of missing data[0m
[30;1m15 | [0m[35m====================================[0m
[30;1m16 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m17 | [0m[35mData at any level of an Awkward Array can be "missing," represented by `None` in Python.[0m
[30;1m18 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m19 | [0m[35mThis functionality is somewhat like NumPy's [masked arrays](https://numpy.org/doc/stable/reference/m[0m
[30;1m20 | [0m[35m[0m
